collections.name: The Gold and Chessboard Problem
collections.description:
The Gold and Chessboard Problem is a serial conceptual artwork that consists of 64 individual pieces. Together they form a chessboard, but each piece stands independently as its own artwork.

The pricing structure is central to the concept. Like the classic chessboard story, the price of each piece doubles with every subsequent sale. Starting from a small initial value, this exponential progression makes later squares increasingly rare and expensive. Prices are calculated based on their weight in gold.

What makes this project groundbreaking is the resale mechanism. Each buyer is entitled to receive their original investment plus 50% once the next piece in the series is sold at a higher price. This creates an evolving financial chain where each sale triggers a return for the previous buyer, blending art ownership with investment dynamics.

This innovative system bridges traditional art, digital assets and finance, making every buyer a co-creator in the artwork's evolving story.
